segment.source: This topic describes User State Migration Tool (USMT) 10.0 return codes and error messages.
segment.target: This topic describes User State Migration Tool (USMT) 10.0 return codes and error messages.

segment.source: Also included is a table listing the USMT return codes with their associated mitigation steps.
segment.target: Also included is a table listing the USMT return codes with their associated mitigation steps.

segment.source: In addition, this topic provides tips to help you use the logfiles to determine why you received an error.
segment.target: In addition, this topic provides tips to help you use the logfiles to determine why you received an error.

segment.source: Understanding the requirements for running USMT can help minimize errors in your USMT migrations.
segment.target: Understanding the requirements for running USMT can help minimize errors in your USMT migrations.

segment.source: For more information, see USMT Requirements.
segment.target: For more information, see USMT Requirements.

segment.source: If you encounter an error in your USMT migration, you can use return codes and the more specific information provided in the associated USMT error messages to troubleshoot the issue and to identify mitigation steps.
segment.target: If you encounter an error in your USMT migration, you can use return codes and the more specific information provided in the associated USMT error messages to troubleshoot the issue and to identify mitigation steps.

segment.source: As a best practice, we recommend that you set verbosity level to 5, /v:5, on the ScanState, LoadState, and USMTUtils command lines so that the most detailed reporting is available in the respective USMT logs.
segment.target: As a best practice, we recommend that you set verbosity level to 5, /v:5, on the ScanState, LoadState, and USMTUtils command lines so that the most detailed reporting is available in the respective USMT logs.

segment.source: You can use a higher verbosity level if you want the log files output to go to a debugger.
segment.target: You can use a higher verbosity level if you want the log files output to go to a debugger.

segment.source: USMT Error Messages
segment.target: USMT Error Messages

segment.source: Error messages provide more detailed information about the migration problem than the associated return code.
segment.target: Error messages provide more detailed information about the migration problem than the associated return code.

segment.source: For example, the ScanState, LoadState, or USMTUtils tool might return a code of "11” (for “USMTINVALIDPARAMETERS") and a related error message that reads "/key and /keyfile both specified".
segment.target: For example, the ScanState, LoadState, or USMTUtils tool might return a code of "11” (for “USMTINVALIDPARAMETERS") and a related error message that reads "/key and /keyfile both specified".

segment.source: The error message is displayed at the command prompt and is identified in the ScanState, LoadState, or USMTUtils log files to help you determine why the return code was received.
segment.target: The error message is displayed at the command prompt and is identified in the ScanState, LoadState, or USMTUtils log files to help you determine why the return code was received.

segment.source: You can obtain more information about any listed Windows application programming interface (API) system error codes by typing net helpmsg on the command line and, then typing the error code number.
segment.target: You can obtain more information about any listed Windows application programming interface (API) system error codes by typing net helpmsg on the command line and, then typing the error code number.

segment.source: For more information about System Error Codes, see this Microsoft Web site.
segment.target: For more information about System Error Codes, see this Microsoft Web site.
